<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-direct-variation-prep" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Proportionality and Direct Variation Prep Activities</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Two varying quantities <m>Q_1</m> and <m>Q_2</m> have a <term>proportional relationship</term> when the ratio between the quantities is constant. That is, <m>Q_1</m> and <m>Q_2</m> have a proportional relationship when 
      <me>
        c = \frac{Q_2}{Q_1}
      </me>
      always has the same value. We call <m>c</m> the <term>constant of proportionality.</term>
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-proportion-or-not">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Peyton is using an app to track data about their recent activity. The tables below show time, <m>T</m>, (measured in minutes) and distance, <m>D</m> from their starting location (measured in miles) data from three of Peyton's recent activity sessions.
        </p>
        <sidebyside>
                <table>
                    <title>Walk</title>
                    <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom = "minor" right="minor" left="minor">
                        <row header="yes">
                            <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>D</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>5</cell>
                            <cell>0.25</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>10</cell>
                            <cell>0.5</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>15</cell>
                            <cell>0.75</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>20</cell>
                            <cell>1.0</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>25</cell>
                            <cell>1.25</cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <table>
                    <title>Hike</title>
                    <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom = "minor" right="minor" left="minor">
                        <row header="yes">
                            <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>D</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>10</cell>
                            <cell>0.5</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>20</cell>
                            <cell>0.75</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>30</cell>
                            <cell>1.0</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>40</cell>
                            <cell>1.5</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>50</cell>
                            <cell>1.75</cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <table>
                    <title>Bike Ride</title>
                    <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom = "minor" right="minor" left="minor">
                        <row header="yes">
                            <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>D</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>10</cell>
                            <cell>2.5</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>20</cell>
                            <cell>5.0</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>30</cell>
                            <cell>7.5</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>40</cell>
                            <cell>10.0</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>50</cell>
                            <cell>12.5</cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
            </sidebyside>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find <m>\frac{D}{T}</m> for each row in the Walk table. Use your results to determine whether Peyton's time and distance on their walk have a proportional relationship.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find <m>\frac{D}{T}</m> for each row in the Hike table. Use your results to determine whether Peyton's time and distance on their hike have a proportional relationship.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find <m>\frac{D}{T}</m> for each row in the Bike Ride table. Use your results to determine whether Peyton's time and distance on their bike ride have a proportional relationship.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the constant of proportionality for each of the activities in which Peyton's time and distance had a proportional relationship?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Interpret the constant of proportionality in context. That is, what does it tell us about the relationship between Peyton's time and distance?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </investigation>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-varies-directly">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        When two quantities have a proportional relationship, it is often useful to rewrite the equation
        <me>
          c = \frac{Q_2}{Q_1}
        </me> 
        as
        <me>Q_2 = c Q_1</me>.
        We sometimes say that <m>Q_2</m> <term>varies directly</term> with respect to <m>Q_1</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use your work from <xref ref="pa-proportion-or-not"/> to write an equation that shows that Peyton's distance varies directly with respect to time for one of their activities.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use your equation to predict Peyton's distance after 65 minutes of activity.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use your equation to predict how long it would take Peyton to go 3.0 miles.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </investigation>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-using-roots-to-solve">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        In this unit, we will need to be able to solve equations of the form <me>y = cx^n</me>, where the values of <m>y</m>, <m>c</m>, and <m>n</m> are known.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Divide by sides by <m>c</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            When <m>n</m> is a positive whole number, take the <term>n-th root</term> of both sides. 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        Here is an example:
      </p>
      <table>
        <title>Solving an equation with an unknown base and a known power.</title>
        <tabular>
          <row>
            <cell><m>24 = 3x^3</m></cell>
            <cell></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>8 = x^3</m></cell>
            <cell>Divide by sides by 3, and compute <m>\frac{24}{3} = 8</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>\sqrt[3]{8} = \sqrt[3]{x^3}</m></cell>
            <cell>Take the 3rd root, <m>\sqrt[3]{\ }</m>, of both sides</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>2 = x</m></cell>
            <cell>Calculate <m>\sqrt[3]{8} = 2</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        The TI-30XIIS calculator can calculate the <m>n</m>th root using 2nd + ^. To calculate <m>\sqrt[3]{8}</m>, for example, press 3, then 2nd, then ^, then 8, then =. We will study roots more carefully in a few lessons, but you will need to be able to use them to solve equations in the next class period.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use roots to find a solution to each of the following equations:
        </p>
      </statement>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>972 = 0.125x^5</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>36 = 2x^3</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>0.5 = 0.02x^2</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In previous math classes, you may have learned that when the power is even, like in <m>0.5 = 0.02x^2</m>, then there are two solutions. You found one of them above. What's the other solution?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </investigation>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-prep-survey-direct-variation">
      <p>
          You'll need to be able to do the following things for this lesson. Rate how confident you are on a scale of 1 - 5 (1 = not confident and 5 = very confident).
      </p>
      <table>
          <tabular bottom = "minor" top = "minor" left = "minor" right = "minor">
              <row header ="yes" bottom = "minor">
                  <cell>Skill or Concept: I can …</cell>
                  <cell>Rating from 1 to 5</cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom = "minor">
                  <cell>Determine whether two quantities have a proportional relationship.</cell>
                  <cell></cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom = "minor">
                  <cell>Find the constant of proportionality for two quantities with a proportional relationship from a data table.</cell>
                  <cell></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                  <cell>Write an equation that shows a quantity <m>Q_2</m> varies directly with respect to another quantity <m>Q_1</m>.</cell>
                  <cell></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>Use roots to solve an equation of the form <m>y = cx^n</m>.</cell>
                <cell></cell>
              </row>
          </tabular>
      </table>
  </investigation>
</section>